04171nam a22006495i 9780292794047DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212008txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927940477 a10.7560/7180742doi  a(DE-B1597)588533  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF385.2b.C64 2008eb 7aHIS0360102bisacsh04a306.097642221 aClemons, Leigh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBranding Texas :bPerforming Culture in the Lone Star State /cLeigh Clemons. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2008  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1.Introduction. Texas and the Performance of Regionality -- t2. “Deep in the Heart”. The Architectural Landscapes of Texan Cultural Memory -- t3. Teaching “Texan”. The Pedagogical Function of the Texas Revolution -- t4. “What’s the Matter with you People?” The Performance of Authentic Behavior in Small-Town Texan Plays -- t5. Selling Texas: Th e Political Branding of Texan Cultural Identity -- t6. Conclusion “Our Flag Still Waves Proudly from the Walls” -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAsk anyone to name an archetypal Texan, and you're likely to get a larger-than-life character from film or television (say John Wayne's Davy Crockett or J. R. Ewing of TV's Dallas) or a politician with that certain swagger (think LBJ or George W. Bush). That all of these figures are white and male and bursting with self-confidence is no accident, asserts Leigh Clemons. In this thoughtful study of what makes a "Texan," she reveals how Texan identity grew out of the history—and, even more, the myth—of the heroic deeds performed by Anglo men during the Texas Revolution and the years of the Republic and how this identity is constructed and maintained by theatre and other representational practices. Clemons looks at a wide range of venues in which "Texanness" is performed, including historic sites such as the Alamo, the battlefield at Goliad, and the San Jacinto Monument; museums such as the Bob Bullock Texas State History Museum; seasonal outdoor dramas such as Texas! at Palo Duro Canyon; films such as John Wayne's The Alamo and the IMAX's Alamo: The Price of Freedom; plays and TV shows such as the Tuna trilogy, Dallas, and King of the Hill; and the Cavalcade of Texas performance at the 1936 Texas Centennial. She persuasively demonstrates that these performances have created a Texan identity that has become a brand, a commodity that can be sold to the public and even manipulated for political purposes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aFolklorezTexasxHistory. 0aGroup identityzTexasxHistory. 0aPerforming artszTexasxHistory. 0aPopular culturezTexasxHistory. 0aTheaterzTexasxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794047423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794047/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK